<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow higher in spite of
disappointing GDP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER trading lower for most of the day on news of weaker economic growth,
US share prices moved into positive territory on a surge of late buying,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 11.62 ahead on balance at
3,425.12. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was a net 0.87 up at 438.89 and the
Nasdaq composite 0.29 firmer at 658.45. Volume on the New York SE totalled
249.7m shares.
Early trading was dominated by a raft of economic data. The good news - a
7,000 decline in weekly jobless claims and a 4.8 per cent rise in March new
house sales - was mostly overshadowed by the long-awaited first-quarter
gross domestic product report.
The Commerce Department announced that GDP grew by an annualised 1.8 per
cent in the quarter, compared with 4.7 per cent growth in the previous three
months. Although the markets had been bracing themselves for a slowdown in
economic growth, the figure was still disappointing, coming in below
forecasts of GDP expansion of 2.3 per cent.
The markets were also unnerved by news of a 3.3 per cent increase in the
implicit price deflator - the measure of inflation published along with the
GDP numbers.
The news of slowing growth, possibly reviving inflation, and generally
depressed equity markets (before yesterday prices had fallen on seven out of
the last eight days) all contributed to the early decline. Late in the
session a rush of buying helped the leading indices end higher on the day.
Improved earnings failed to lift General Motors. The car manufacturer
reported first-quarter net income of 42 cents a share, a turnround from the
big loss a year earlier. Although the figures were ahead of analysts'
expectations, investors took the opportunity to book some profits earned in
the stock's recent climb (it started yesterday within Dollars 2 of its
52-week high) and GM shed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 40 7/8 in volume of 3.6m
shares.
UAL fell Dollars 4 7/8 to Dollars 140 5/8 after the airline group reported a
larger than expected quarterly loss of Dollars 5.92 a share, prior to an
extraordinary charge.
American International Group jumped Dollars 4 5/8 to Dollars 124 1/2 after
the insurer unveiled operating income of Dollars 2.24 a share, up from
Dollars 1.91 a year ago.
On the Nasdaq market, President Riverboat rose Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 323
after Missouri legislators passed a bill that will pave the way for
riverboat gambling to begin in the state.
Canada
TORONTO forged ahead in heavy volume, helped by strong showings in
transportation, banking and gold issues. The TSE 300 index climbed 44.9 to
3,755.1. Rises led falls by 443 to 262 on 77.5m shares traded.
Dealers said a swift fall in interest rates and recovery in the Canadian
dollar fuelled gains in banking shares.
Twelve of the 14 stock groups rose. Transportation led the way, advancing
3.39 per cent, followed by financial services, up 2.63 per cent. Golds added
1.93 per cent.
</TEXT>
