<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / International Company News: Kleinwort Benson rejects US
allegations by PaineWebber
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK investment bank Kleinwort Benson defended itself yesterday against
allegations that several new senior officers at its US asset management
affiliate conspired to steal the core of a fixed income asset management
department run by PaineWebber, the Wall Street securities house.
In announcing the appointment of Mr Stephen Canter as executive chairman and
chief executive officer and Mr Emad Zikry as president and chief investment
officer of its New York-based subsidiary Kleinwort Benson International
Investment, the UK bank denied that the two men, who until last week were
employed at the PaineWebber unit Mitchell Hutchins Institutional Investors,
had solicited employees or clients of MHII, or had denigrated MHII, while
still at that company.
Angered by the defections, PaineWebber yesterday filed a civil lawsuit in
New York against three former MHII executives and Kleinwort's US affiliate.
In the suit, PaineWebber alleges that Mr Canter and Mr Zikry, along with Mr
Thomas Goepfert, another senior MHII officer who left to join Kleinwort,
recruited other MHII employees while still at the firm and used confidential
and proprietary client information, including investment objectives and fee
structures, to solicit MHII clients.
PaineWebber also says that the executives undertook a mass solicitation of
MHII clients one day after they resigned from MHII, and persuaded other MHII
staff to leave the firm and join Kleinwort.
In London late yesterday the UK bank said that it had not yet received
notification of the lawsuit. But Mr Lesley Knox, chairman of Kleinwort's US
money management subsidiary, said the accusations outlined in press reports
of the impending legal action were 'totally unfounded'.
In New York meanwhile, PaineWebber was playing down the significance of the
staff departures at MHII - in total, 10 people left the firm - while still
angrily decrying the actions of the three executives who left for Kleinwort.
Ms Joyce Fensterstock, president of PaineWebber's mutual fund unit and the
executive who has taken over as president of MHII, said that only one client
had removed its account from the firm because of the uncertainty surrounding
the defections.
She was confident the client would return, but said she may lose others: 'We
will lose some accounts because when there's this kind of upheaval . . .
some people use it as an excuse to move their money.'
PaineWebber insisted that the financial impact of the defections would be
minimal. The fixed income unit where the departed executives worked manages
Dollars 4bn of assets and generated revenues of almost Dollars 8m last year,
out of a total of more than Dollars 300m in recurring fee revenues generated
at the PaineWebber group.
</TEXT>
