<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / International Company News: Cominco suspends half-year
dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMINCO, the Canadian base metals group buffetted by a series of setbacks in
recent years, has suspended its semi-annual dividend.
The Vancouver-based company also said yesterday that it plans to seek
financial compensation from Lurgi, the German engineering firm, for a
disastrous investment in a CDollars 160m (USDollars 126m) lead smelter at
Trail, British Columbia.
The smelter, which uses technology supplied by Lurgi, has been idle since
shortly after it was commissioned in late-1989.
Mr Norman Keevil, chairman, told the annual meeting yesterday that Cominco
now expects to spend CDollars 100m to modify the smelter. He said the
facility will probably be converted from Lurgi's QSL process to the Kivcet
technology developed in Kazakhstan.
Mr Keevil said that tests have shown that the Kivcet process 'has the
reduction capacity and availability that we need at Trail'.
Cominco paid a semi-annual dividend of 15 Canadian cents a share last
December. It suffered a loss of CDollars 30.2m last year following a
CDollars 41.3m setback in 1991.
Cominco has also struggled to achieve full production at its new Red Dog
zinc mine in Alaska, and has been hit by falling metal prices.
