<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Rival leaders to meet on Bosnia peace proposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER, PHILIP STEPHENS and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LORD OWEN and Mr Cyrus Vance, joint mediators to the Bosnian dispute, said
last night at the UN that they were convening a meeting this weekend with
Bosnian Serb, Croat and Moslem leaders as well as the presidents of Croatia,
Yugoslavia, Serbia and Montenegro.
A spokesman for Mr Vance and Lord Owen said the meeting was prompted by a
decision of the Bosnian Serbs to reconsider the Vance-Owen peace plan they
had rejected earlier this week.
The meeting, scheduled for Saturday and Sunday in Athens, would include
Bosnian president Alija Izetbegovic, Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic,
Bosnian Croat leader Mate Boban, Serbian president Slobodan Milosovic,
Croatian president Franjo Tudjman and others.
It is seen as a last-ditch attempt to save the Vance-Owen peace plan and to
put pressure on the Bosnian Serb Assembly when it meets on Wednesday to
reconsider its initial rejection. The Athens meeting will also see Mr
Vance's handover of his position as mediator to Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg,
former Norwegian foreign minister.
Western governments yesterday were struggling to maintain a united front on
proposals for outside military intervention in Bosnia, amid growing reports
of disagreements over what option should be chosen.
A senior Nato official said the chances of decisive western military
intervention in Bosnia were fading. The official blamed European opposition
to the use of force which had proved 'highly influential' with the Clinton
administration and closed military options.
EC foreign ministers this week expressed strong reservations about military
intervention and defence chiefs on both sides of the Atlantic went public
with their concerns about using force without clear-cut goals.
In Washington, President Bill Clinton is struggling to reach a consensus
among his own civilian and military advisers on US action to force the
Bosnian Serbs to sign the Vance-Owen plan. A decision is expected in the
next few days.
Britain, however, yesterday indicated it was ready to back a US ultimatum
threatening air strikes against Serbian forces in Bosnia if the US
administration agreed to maintain the international arms embargo.
