<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Hurd firm on Bosnia arms embargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S implacable opposition to the lifting of the embargo on arms
sales to the former Yugoslavia was underlined yesterday by Mr Douglas Hurd.
In a Commons debate which saw the Labour party call for the west to threaten
air strikes on Serbian supply lines, the foreign secretary stressed that
there could no military solution to the civil war in Bosnia.
Speaking as Whitehall officials said negotiations with Washington over the
Bosnian crisis were still far from reaching a conclusion, Mr Hurd said that
in the end a negotiated political settlement would provide the only durable
answer.
But acknowledging the intense frustration in Washington at the refusal of
the Serbs to respond to sanctions, he made it clear that the threat of air
strikes remained a live option to intensify pressure on Serbia.
In a carefully crafted speech which sought to balance anxiety to avoid an
open rift with Washington with scepticism over the effectiveness of military
action, Mr Hurd said that 'the only alternative to a real negotiated
solution is indefinite fighting and suffering'.
His remarks came as Conservative backbench MPs warned against the risk of
military entanglement in the civil war. The overwhelming mood among MPs was
that air strikes should be used only as a last resort.
There were repeated calls - accepted by the foreign secretary - that the
British troops serving with the United Nations in Bosnia should be withdrawn
if they risked coming under direct attack from Serbian forces.
Mr Hurd, echoing the sentiments expressed by Mr John Major in earlier
exchanges with Labour leader Mr John Smith, set out four clear priorities
for policy towards Serbia:
To provide a framework, through the Vance-Owen plan, for a political
solution.
To apply pressure to end Serbian aggression.
To maintain the humanitarian aid effort.
To prevent the fighting from spreading to other provinces of the former
Yugoslavia and beyond.
Stressing that international solidarity was 'essential' if peace was to be
restored, Mr Hurd said that if the political and military objectives were
carefully defined 'air strikes might have a value as a threat, to deter the
Bosnian Serbs from certain strategies. If defied, actual strikes could
prevent them from adopting those strategies.'
The foreign secretary won support from Labour for an unequivocal rejection
of any move to lift the arms embargo. That would risk spreading the conflict
and 'far from tilting the balance towards the Bosnian Moslems, lifting the
embargo could lead to an increase in the supply of weapons to the Serbs and
Croats'.
Mr Smith told the House that the acknowledged risks of limited air strikes
were increasingly outweighed by the real dangers of inaction.
He said the Serbs would continue to flout the UN's authority unless
subjected to an ultimatum backed by a credible threat to their lines of
communication and supply.
Mr John Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, clashed with Ms Clare Short
(Lab Birmingham Ladywood) who argued that if there was no willingness to
create 'safe havens' and no willingness to stop Serb aggression the Bosnians
were entitled to arms to defend themselves.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, said inaction had closed off the
best and less risky options, and that continued failure of leadership would
lead to a completely uncontrollable situation.
Replying to the debate, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, said the
Serbs should not be allowed to take for granted certain forms of policy or
inaction on the part of the international community.
The debate, on a technical motion for the adjournment, ended without a
division.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
