<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Nuts reprieved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORTILLA CHIPS, pistachio nuts in their shells, packets of poppadums and
other savoury snacks have been granted a reprieve from value added tax,
Customs and Excise ruled yesterday, Andrew Jack writes.
Following consultation with snack manufacturers and other trade bodies
Customs has rejected suggestions that 17.5 per cent VAT should be imposed on
a wider range of snacks.
The decision follows a Customs consultation document in March last year
which suggested the possibility of widening the definition of snacks that
would not be classified as food.
The clause - originally drafted for purchase tax introduced in 1969 and
incorporated into VAT legislation in 1974 - said there would be no
zero-rating for potato-based products, for those made from the swelling of
cereal products or for salted or roasted nuts, except for those in their
shells.
That has left a growing number of anomalies, as more exotic snacks have been
introduced in the past two decades. Snacks which are currently zero-rated
include sugar-coated biscuits, Twiglets and gingerbread women dipped in
caramel - though not in chocolate.
Customs now accepts that VAT can be recovered by builders of new houses for
the purchase of materials for fitted furniture, it said yesterday.
The action follows a ruling in the High Court following an assessment
relating to McLeans Homes (Midland) Ltd.
</TEXT>
