<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Privatisations bill set for
programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEASURES TO streamline the process of giving parliamentary approval to
future privatisations are likely to be included in next year's legislative
programme.
The government is planning to incorporate a measure making it unnecessary to
enact specific paving bills giving ministers the power to sell individual
government-owned entities.
Senior ministers are expected to finalise next week their decision on which
bills are to be put forward in the parliamentary session beginning in
November.
Deregulation, law and order, and improvements in public services have
emerged as the main themes of the programme, which was discussed by the
cabinet yesterday following a presentation from Mr Tony Newton, the Commons
leader.
It is so far unclear whether the privatisation measure is to come to the
House as a stand-alone bill or take the form of additional clauses
'piggy-backing' on another bill going through parliament.
One candidate for such an approach would be a general deregulation bill put
forward by the Department of Trade and Industry. One minister said yesterday
he would be 'astonished' if the privatisation measure was not included in
one form or another.
The deregulation theme is also expected to feature in the deregulation of
London buses and changes to the law on Sunday trading.
A criminal justice bill, a police bill, and action to curb new age
travellers will underline the government's commitment to regaining the
initiative on law and order.
Further action on improving the efficiency and quality of public services
will be shown by, for example, measures such as the bill setting up the
environmental protection agency, and re-organising local government in
Wales.
The fate of the legislation needed to equalise the pension age still hangs
in the balance, with ministers divided on whether to move ahead with the
plans in spite of their probable unpopularity, or to delay the controversial
move until the following year.
The programme may well not contain as many bills as other parliamentary
sessions, but will involve a high proportion of substantial measures.
The government has not required paving legislation to carry out every
privatisation in the last 14 years, but a bill was enacted earlier this year
covering both British Coal and British Rail.
Among the principal prospective sell-offs to be affected if current
proposals are included in the legislative timetable could be the Post
Office. The government recently decided to delay that sale until the 1994-95
session at the earliest.
</TEXT>
