<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour plan focuses on skills
training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS FOR a Labour economic strategy emphasising greater investment in
skills training - and aiming the party away from engaging too heavily in
debate with Tories on taxation - will be unveiled this weekend.
The document drawn up by Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, forms part of
Labour's rolling policy review and will be presented next week to its
elected National Policy Forum, which represents all sections of the party.
are Papers on Europe policy and on constitutional reform, excluding
proportional representation, are also to be submitted to the forum.
Mr Brown argues that over the next decade the competitive advantages of
industrialised nations will stem increasingly from the quality of their
workforce, rather than in-digenous resources.
He attempts to shift the debate in the Labour party away from taxation and
public borrowing - traditionally weak areas for the party in elections - and
towards how the state, possibly in conjunction with the private sector, can
improve education, training and infrastructure.
The focus on workforce skills fits with calls by Mr John Smith, Labour
leader, for the party to put an increasing emphasis on fostering the
aspirations of individuals.
Mr Brown's paper, presented as a fundamental assesment of Britain's economic
prospects into the next century, argues for a system of managed exchange
rates, perhaps based on a reformed European exchange rate mechanism.
It calls for a greater emphasis on measures aimed at tackling unemployment.
The paper is expected to be discussed at Labour's annual conference in
October.
