<PROFILE>_AN-DD3B1ACPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930430
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / The Lloyd's Business Plan: Record losses at Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S EXPECTS to report record losses of between Pounds 2.5bn and Pounds
2.8bn for 1990 when it reports results for the year in June.
The figure is artificially high because it counts some losses twice. When
syndicates that insure the legal liabilities of agents in the market (the
so-called errors and omissions insurers) and syndicates that provide
stop-loss insurance (personal reinsurance for Names) set aside sums for
possible future claims, the market as a whole provides for the same claim
twice. Without this, Lloyd's says, losses would be near the Pounds 2bn of
1989.
</TEXT>
