<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / The Lloyd's Business Plan: Main Objectives of The Business
Plan
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Global profits to reach  Pounds 900m by the 1995 accounting year
Names to get a 33 per cent pre-tax return
A target of 20 per cent pre-tax return for incorporated Names
To cut the cost base by at least  Pounds 190m
To reduce personnel from some 12,000 to 9,500
A move to more direct leadership, intervening where necessary
To engender a sense of collective responsibility in the market
To introduce a risk profiling system to monitor exposure of
syndicates and allow capacity management
To establish a small audit unit
To facilitate central production of business information
To extend the requirement for professional qualifications
A move to one-year accounting
To reconfigure central support services to form closer links
between marketing services and Lloyd's market associations
To create a 'ring-fence' to free Names from run-off years and
protect new capital from old year liabilities by:
 - building information bases on pre-1986 liabilities by 1995
 - in 1995, reinsure all pre-1986 liabilities into new company
 - reinsure 1986-1993 years of account into 1994 accounting year
 - reinsure remaining 'open years' into CentreWrite
Active pursuit of negotiated settlement for outstanding legal disputes
To establish a new strategy for collection of debts by the end of June
More proactive and more independent regulation
Full electronic business processing by 1996 including:
 - connection mandatory by end 1993
 - all business supported by electronic version of insurance
   contract by 1996
To establish central policy preparation unit
To establish specialist claims unit for asbestos, pollution and
health hazards by the end of 1993
To replace current claims scheme with a single scheme by January 1994
To expand the application of technology to claims support
To create a unified processing structure for London market in the
long term
To set maximum allowable managing agency fees
To establish external reviews of projected syndicate expenses
The full disclosure of agency staff remuneration
The establishment of a central services unit to carry out members'
agents' administrative functions by 1994
To introduce Mapas (members' agents' pooling arrangements) and
Manuac (managing agents' unitised accounting) by the 1994 accounting
year
To create licensed Lloyd's advisers to provide advice to
incorporated capital
To provide well-managed services to facilitate the run-off of
syndicates and Names by the end of 1993
To admit incorporated capital for 1994
A target capacity of  Pounds 10bn- Pounds 12bn by 1997
To manage aggregate capacity:
 - setting yearly limit and allowing corporate entities to 'bid'
for spare capacity
 - encourage quota share and consortia arrangements
 - develop flexible premium income limits
Introduce high-liquidity Names:
 - liquid assets  Pounds 500,000
 - minimum deposit  Pounds 200,000
 - confirmed means of 50 per cent of overall premium limit.
Mapa-only Names to underwrite with 25 per cent deposit
To end restriction on  Pounds 3m upper premium income limit
To include US dollar securities as acceptable Names' deposit
To consolidate market position through simplification of business
channels to Lloyd's and market-led initiatives
To extend existing central technical services
To broaden profile in Europe, Asia and the Pacific
To implement plans through six programmes, each led by a senior
executive, answerable to the Market Board.
</TEXT>
