<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Barclays to launch telephone banking trial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARCLAYS IS to launch a pilot telephone banking service for 10,000 personal
customers from July. It said yesterday this was one of a series of projects
which would revolutionise the way it provided services over the next decade.
The experimental Barclaycall service will operate from Coventry, offering
telephone banking to customers from 39 branches. The bank is also extending
its personal loans telephone sales operation across the country.
The moves represent an integrated effort to transform retail banking and are
likely to be examined by competitors trying to find ways of reducing costs
while improving service.
Mr Bill Gordon, managing director of the bank's UK branch network, said it
had decided to offer a telephone back-up to branch services rather than
establish a separate telephone bank on the model of Firstdirect, Midland's
subsidiary.
'The customer still values being able to deal face to face with staff in a
branch occasionally, and we want to maintain that at the same time as
offering a new service over the telephone,' said Mr Gordon.
Several large banks such as Royal Bank of Scotland are experimenting with
telephone services. Barclays emphasised that it hoped to extend the
telephone service to small business customers.
Mr Gordon said the bank, which last year made a pre-tax loss of Pounds 242m,
was trying to 'sharpen' its risk-management methods. Among initiatives
disclosed to staff at Barclays' 2,200 branches yesterday are:
Each cashier will have a terminal to authorise cash payment electronically
from any branch. The system, which will be fully implemented by next year,
will answer balance inquiries and be capable of transferring sums between
accounts. Storage and handling of securities such as debentures over company
assets and personal life assurance policies will be centralised. Data about
securities will be accessed by local branch managers using computers.
A personal computer-based risk assessment system for local managers to judge
loans for medium-sized and large companies will be piloted in two regions in
the second half of this year.
A central database holding all customer records and capable of updating
accounts immediately will be installed across branches by the end of next
year, allowing accounts to be opened by a single entry of data.
Staff in seven of the bank's 23 regions will work on a new risk-management
system for personal loans. The bank is likely to start testing new risk
management methods later this year before deciding on the changes to
implement.
Two branches in London will be test sites for the whole range of
initiatives.
Barclaycall will offer a series of services including bill payments, balance
inquiries and amendment of standing orders.
Barclays has established a new central sales and service unit in its banking
division to develop services. The Barclayloan Direct service offering loans
by telephone will start operating nationally later this year.
Meanwhile, Bifu, the bank staff union, issued a writ yesterday against
Barclays Bank claiming damages on behalf of 400 computer staff suspended
without pay in March 1991 for refusing to take a loyalty pledge during an
overtime ban.
Mr Rob MacGregor, Bifu's assistant general secretary, said: 'It has taken a
long time to collate all the evidence but we are now confident of success.'
Mr MacGregor added that the bank would be 'called to account' by the courts
for the 'disgraceful treatment' of its workforce.
Barclays' AGM, Page 20
</TEXT>
