<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / More pilots urged for ships
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
COMMERCIAL PRESSURE to take the most direct route between Norway and North
America forced the master of the oil tanker Braer to risk polluting the
Shetland coastline, professional pilots told the Donaldson public inquiry
yesterday.
Captain Phillip Grey, in a joint submission for the Deep Sea and North Sea
Pilots' Associations, said the safer - but longer - route to the Atlantic
was through the North Sea and the English Channel.
Captain Grey said: 'He (the master) would have been safe, but probably soon
out of work. His charterer could claim the extra distance and time
involved.'
Pilot organisations urged the inquiry, which is considering the wider
implications of the oil spill in January, to recommend greater use of
pilotage to take vessels along vulnerable coasts.
The Department of Transport has refused to support calls for mandatory
pilotage for such routes as the Minches and the Pentland Firth. In a
memorandum to the inquiry the government said it would be unnecessary and
might be prohibitively expensive. 'The department is not aware of any water
around the UK, outside harbours and regularly used by shipping, where the
risk of collision or grounding is high and where the compulsory requirement
for a pilot would be likely to reduce that risk.'
The hearing resumes on May 11.
</TEXT>
