<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Daf truck plant attracts rival bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 40M-PLUS management buy-out of Leyland Daf's truck assembly plant
in Lancashire was agreed in outline early yesterday. Within hours, however,
a new bidder had opened talks with the company's administrative receiver to
try to thwart the deal.
Mr Ian McKinnon, who led the successful management buy-out of Leyland Bus in
1985, saw Mr John Talbot of Arthur Andersen, the joint receiver, late
yesterday afternoon. He wants to buy the assembly plant in Leyland, the axle
plant at Albion in Glasgow and the spare parts business in Chorley,
Lancashire.
Leyland Bus was sold to Volvo in 1987. Mr McKinnon is now a senior executive
with Alcan, the aluminium company, which is not connected with his bid.
He is offering to better the truck assembly buy-out. With the parts business
valued at more than Pounds 100m, industry estimates suggest he would need
more than Pounds 200m to succeed in buying everything.
Mr Talbot said the outline agreement with the management team covered price
and 'other critical factors', but was subject to contract. Both sides aim to
finalise the deal in the latter half of May. Mr Talbot said in the meanwhile
he would 'continue to talk to other interested parties'.
Mr McKinnon declined to name two City financial institutions he said were
behind him. They still have to carry out their own investigations after
obtaining more information from the receiver, and senior debt has still to
be negotiated with clearing banks.
His advisers include Dickson Minto, a firm of London corporate lawyers
specialising in acquisitions and buy-outs. Mr McKinnon was operating from
the firm's offices yesterday.
The management buy-out team believes other bidders are now out of the
running. Its case is that the factory depends on being able to sell trucks
throughout the whole of Europe and it has negotiated an agreement with Daf's
European dealer network to achieve this.
It has a supply agreement with the spare parts business and another to take
65 per cent of the Albion axle output. The Glasgow plant also supplies
Leyland Daf vans in Birmingham, which was bought separately by its
management last week. This interdependent circle of demand and supply is
understood to guarantee the future - and eventual saleability - of all parts
of the former Daf business.
Mr McKinnon wants to offer the receiver a less complicated deal, taking the
whole business and running his own sales and marketing operation.
Under the management buy-out deal Lancashire Enterprises, the privatised
economic development arm of Lancashire County Council, would buy the entire
230-acre Leyland Daf site and its 1.8m sq ft of factory, and lease 800,000
sq ft for truck assembly to the management buy-out team. Lancashire
Enterprises would develop the rest as a technology park.
The deal was negotiated by Mr Paul Southern, northern corporate finance
partner of Coopers &amp; Lybrand in Leeds.
</TEXT>
