<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Nursing home staff to take Ernst &amp; Young to tribunal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NINE NURSING home employees are taking receivers Ernst &amp; Young to an
industrial tribunal in a dispute over 'laying on' money - the first week's
wages which are withheld as a week in hand and paid to workers when their
employment ceases.
The employees of a nursing home near Darlington, Co Durham, claim the
receivers should have paid them their laying on money when the home was
sold.
Ernst &amp; Young, which ran the home in receivership for more than 18 months
after Stainford, the previous owner, went under, is contesting the claim.
'We've taken legal advice and our view is Ernst &amp; Young was never their
employer,' said the firm, which is being advised by Newcastle-based
solicitors Dickinson Dees.
Originally, 19 employees at the 58-bed Greenacres nursing home, formerly
called the Gainford nursing home, applied for a tribunal hearing, but 10
pulled out after a pre-hearing assessment.
The application is scheduled to be heard on Tuesday in Middlesbrough.
</TEXT>
<XX>
