<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Office building cheaper in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COST of developing a large office block is almost a third cheaper in the
US than in the UK, according to a study commissioned by BAA, the airports
company.
BAA spends about Pounds 250m a year on large construction projects and is
proposing to build a Pounds 900m fifth terminal at Heathrow Airport.
It said yesterday that, as a test, it asked contractors in North Carolina to
tender for a 200,000 sq ft office block identical to a Pounds 17.1m
development by British Airways at Heathrow which is due to be completed this
year.
Lynton, BAA's property subsidiary, commissioned Bovis Construction, the UK
contractor, and Davis Langdon &amp; Everest, quantity surveyors, to tender for a
similar project at an airport in Charlotte, North Carolina, where labour and
material costs are similar to those in Britain.
It was found that the offices built to US designs and specifications were 32
per cent cheaper at Pounds 11.65m than in the UK. Construction costs were
marginally higher in the US at Pounds 17.14m if identical designs and
specifications were used.
Mr Gordon Edington, Lynton's chairman and BAA's property director, said that
the main reasons for differences in costs were that US developers used more
standard designs and common components.
Developers also spent longer preparing detailed designs and organising a job
before starting building work, saving valuable time during construction.
Mr Edington said: 'US architects and engineers spend less time re-inventing
solution wheels and are more ready to incorporate standard technical
solutions into their designs.'
The flood of construction companies which have gone into receivership is
likely to increase as the UK economy recovers and building costs rise, the
EC Harris construction cost consultancy warned yesterday.
Mr Christopher Vickers, chairman, said: 'Pressures on contractors are
increasing from a number of directors and not just from rises in input
costs.'
The failure of customers meant large losses on jobs while contractors were
receiving less interest on progress payment money held on deposit for
sub-contractors, so cashflow was likely to fall.
EC Harris said in its quarterly economic survey that contractors bidding
fixed prices on projects unlikely to be completed for up to two years could
run into serious difficulties due to rises in building material prices.
Producers of steel, glass, plasterboard, cement and aggregates have
announced price rises this year. EC Harris said: 'The latest increases in
material prices look set to stick because the costs of alternative cheap
imports have now increased 15 per cent due to sterling's devaluation.'
It said that defaults by customers were adding to the pressures on
contractors.
</TEXT>
