<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Most of London bomb area opens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 90 per cent of the area in the City closed because of the IRA bomb at
the weekend has been opened to building keyholders to allow repairs to go
ahead.
Much of the remaining 21-acre area will be opened progressively during the
next few days, but Mr Colin Snowden, the City engineer, said yesterday that
it would take some weeks to open the streets close to the site of the
explosion. The area of Bishopsgate from Wormwood Street to St Helen's Place
is likely to remain closed for two months.
Mr Snowden said: 'We have made good progress in the five days since the
explosion. We have succeeded in getting things virtually back to normal
thanks to the heroic efforts of the police and all other services.'
Buildings near the heart of the blast are being cleared of glass and debris,
and considerable rebuilding needs to be done on a wrecked sewer beneath the
bomb crater.
Mr Snowden confirmed that 25 buildings had been badly damaged and 30 had
sustained moderate damage. Decisions on whether to demolish or refurbish
will be taken by the owners, their technical advisers, and insurers.
He said the clearing-up process, involving nearly 500 tonnes of broken glass
and debris, had cost the City Corporation about Pounds 300,000. Some of this
will be recovered from property owners.
Buildings that suffered most damage were those made of reinforced concrete.
</TEXT>
