<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / Council isolated on school test plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LONDON Borough of Wandsworth's plan to pay supply teachers to administer
national curriculum tests, which face the threat of boycotts by teachers,
seemed unlikely to be followed by other education authorities yesterday.
Wandsworth is paying Pounds 20,000 out of its education budget to employ
teams of supply teachers to invigilate and mark tests for 14-year-olds.
Local education authorities in England and Wales have a legal duty to
implement the tests for their schools, as do the heads and governors of
grant-maintained schools which have opted out of education authority
control.
Wandsworth intends to pass the results of its tests to the review of the
national curriculum being conducted by Sir Ron Dearing. He has said that he
needs completed tests to improve them for next year.
Mr Edward Lister, leader of Wandsworth, said it would be possible for other
authorities to do the same. 'Ours is a local initiative, but obviously other
authorities are in exactly the same position as we are and they've got to
steer through this problem. There are probably enough supply teachers
around,' he said.
According to the Department for Education, there are about 300,000 inactive
teachers in England and Wales, compared with about 400,000 working teachers.
However, the National Association of Governors and Managers cast doubt on
whether enough teachers with adequate specialist qualifications were
available to allow all schools to take the same route. It said the
Wandsworth plan was impracticable.
Mr David Hart, general secretary of the National Association of Head
Teachers, said: 'It's a total misreading of the statutory assessment and
testing arrangements to believe that you can pull in outsiders and expect
them to undertake that job with the knowledge and the skill which would be
brought to that task by the teachers in the schools themselves.'
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, welcomed Wandsworth's move but
stopped short of urging other councils to follow its lead. 'I applaud what
Wandsworth has done. They are using their own resources. They're using their
own school inspectors to go into the schools and make sure that the tests
are taken,' he said, adding that it was up to individual councils to take
similar decisions.
Wandsworth only has four secondary schools, and larger education authorities
might not have the resources.
The Association of Metropolitan Authorities and the Association of County
Councils, which represent local education authorities, said none of their
members planned to follow Wandsworth's lead.
</TEXT>
