<HEADLINE>
FT  30 APR 93 / G7 pledges closer policy co-ordination
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Group of Seven leading industrial countries yesterday broadened the
scope of international economic co-operation with the aim of creating
sustained non-inflationary growth in the world economy.
In a communique notable for its plain language, they agreed that they should
work together to resolve long-term structural issues as well as short-term
problems.
At the end of the meeting of the finance ministers and central bank
governors of the US, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada,
participants agreed that the gathering had been harmonious and constructive
 -in contrast to some recent meetings. Mr Yoshiro Hayashi, Japanese finance
minister, said the countries 'reached a common understanding' about a range
of issues.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US treasury secretary, said the meeting helped 'lay the
basis for further actions to meet the challenges ahead. We can do more and
we should, and I am optimistic that we will.'
Mr Michel Camdessus, managing director of the International Monetary Fund,
said the G7 nations had agreed a 'global strategy for growth' and a
'mutually reinforcing effort for recovery.' He hailed a significant change
in attitude compared with a G7 meeting last September when, he said, all
countries blamed each other for the world's economic problems.
The communique commited the G7 countries to implementing already announced
policies to promote growth and deal with problems such as excessive fiscal
deficits.
The ministers agreed that by the time of the World Economic summit in Tokyo
in July they would produce a report discussing structural measures to be
taken in their countries. These would include: the reform of labour markets;
ways to increase savings and investment; better focused spending on
infrastructure and education; action to cut spiralling health care costs and
ways of coping with the economic problems of ageing populations.
They said that co-operative action and sound economic policies at home,
together with such structural reform and further efforts to liberalise trade
would help create conditions in foreign exchange markets that were in line
with the economic fundamentals of the main industrial countries.
They agreed exchange rate volatility was 'undesirable', although
participants said relatively little time was spent on the exchange rate
issue. In a passage designed to assuage Japanese concerns about the recent
sharp rise of the yen against the dollar, they restated their continued
commitment to close co-operation in foreign exchange markets.
Mr Bentsen said he was optimistic that there would be further interest rate
reductions in Europe and that Japan's fiscal stimulus package would help
reduce its trade imbalance.
Both Mr Hayashi and Mr Bentsen said the prospects were good for further
lowering of European interest rates, but refused to comment on the need for
early cuts in German rates.
'That is a matter for the German authorities,' he said.
Mr Edmond Alphandery, the French economics minister, said there was plenty
of room for lower German interest rates but said France would not seek to
drive rates down and would follow the market.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the German Bundesbank president, said there was no
demand that it give up its cautious easing of interest rates.
The ministers welcomed the results of the Russian referendum. Mr Horst
Kohler, state secretary in the German finance ministry, said that IMF
support under the new systemic transformation facility could flow to Russia
as soon as next month.
The atmosphere of the gathering was improved by Germany's decision this week
to lower its market interest rates, a step that may ease the way to lower
interest rates across Europe.
The intervention by the US Federal Reserve to curb the rapid rise of the yen
on foreign exchange markets also drew the teeth from potential controversy
by easing Japan's worries about the threat to its export competitiveness.
</TEXT>
