<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: Bic's US unit slips into deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BIC, the French consumer products company best-known for its ballpoint pens
and disposable razors, yesterday announced that its US subsidiary fell into
the red in the first quarter of this year with a loss of Dollars 700,000
against a Dollars 7.9m net profit a year ago.
The US company has been hit by the exceptional cost of adapting to the new
regulations on accounting for pension and medical insurance contributions
for its employees. This change, all of which was absorbed in the
first-quarter figures, cost the company Dollars 9.8m, thereby pulling it
into deficit during the first three months of the year.
Without the change in accounting regulations Bic's US subsidiary would have
been in the black during the first quarter. Its turnover rose by 15 per cent
to Dollars 101.2m in the first three months of 1993 from Dollars 88.1m in
1992. Net profits rose by 15 per cent to Dollars 9.1m from Dollars 7.9m.
</TEXT>
