<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: Sweden to keep 25% in Celsius
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Swedish government will retain a minority stake of 25 per cent in
Celsius Industries after this summer's privatisation of the country's
leading defence group.
A further 21 per cent of shares are to be taken up by four Swedish financial
institutions, while 43 per cent will be offered to domestic and foreign
investors, Celsius employees and the general public, according to the
government.
The remaining 11 per cent will be held by Nobel Industries, which sold its
defence electronics activities to Celsius for SKr1.55bn (Dollars 215m) in
February.
The shares have not been priced, but the group's value is estimated at
SKr3bn.
The new ownership structure ensures Celsius remains in Swedish hands. There
are no formal restrictions on foreign ownership, but the state retains the
right to block hostile foreign bids.
The government said Celsius would be able to take a more active part in the
broader restructuring of the European defence industry if it is was in
private hands and had access to external risk capital. It is was hoping a
number of new industrial owners would subscribe to the share offer.
Celsius shares are to be listed on the Stockholm stock exchange with effect
from June 23. The privatisation prospectus will be published on May 10, and
the offer period runs from May 17 to June 4.
The Celsius privatisationis part of the government's privatisation programme
embracing 35 state-owned groups.
</TEXT>
