<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Billionaire imposes capitalist rule: President of Volga
republic makes even Yeltsin seem timid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS the line that Russian President Boris Yeltsin has perhaps always
dreamt of delivering.
With a dead-pan face Mr Kursan Khalmg-Tangch, the newly elected president of
the Russian republic of Kalmykia, yesterday announced that he had sacked the
government.
'We have offered them opportunities to become private farmers. They can do
some useful business then,' he told a stunned press conference in Moscow. He
calmly added that he would impose presidential rule, abolish most
ministries, outlaw the KGB, cut subsidies, slash taxes - and dole out
Dollars 100 (Pounds 65) to every citizen of the Kalmyk republic to let them
join in a programme of radical economic reform.
Tucked on the mouth of the Volga river, the Kalmyk republic, which is
blessed with oil, sheep and caviar, first shot to political fame earlier
this month when it elected Mr Khalmg-Tangch, a 30-year-old local businessman
and rouble billionaire
Running on a political platform that promised 'economic shock reforms' for
the republic, Mr Khalmg-Tangch announced that he was 'neither a communist
nor a democrat but a capitalist'.
In practice, this translates into a vision that takes as its inspiration the
rapid economic growth of South East Asia. Under the plans unveiled
yesterday, the president will assume direct control of all economic
enterprises. Local elected bodies will be abolished, political opposition
discouraged, and foreign investors given free rein to engage in virtually
tax-free business.
Meanwhile, mindful of his Kalmyk Buddhist Mongol heritage, Mr Khalmg-Tangch
will personally finance the construction of a Buddhist temple. He is also
inviting the Dalai Lama to take up residence. A specialist in Japanese
history, Mr Khalmg-Tangch has built a successful business career by
specialising in joint ventures with South Korean and Japanese partners.
With his own large financial resources and links with South East Asian
businesses, Mr Khalmg-Tangch says he is so confident that he can finance
reform that the republic will no longer accept subsidies from Moscow. But
whether the 350,000-strong population of Kalmykia will be able to tolerate
these radical changes remains more dubious.
It also remains to be seen whether the Russian parliament will return the
compliment and let Kalmykia's challenge pass unheeded. 'What Russia needs
now is a strong leader,' said Mr Khalmg-Tangch, yesterday. He added that
after lengthy talks with Mr Yeltsin, the Russian president had expressed an
interest in Kalmykia's programme as a 'mini-model' for Russia.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9131 Executive and Legislative Combined.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
