<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Telecoms sector weakens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, STEVE THOMPSON and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TWO companies representing the UK's telecoms duopoly, BT and Cable and
Wireless, sharply underperformed the market. They suffered from increasing
worries of competition in the UK and overseas from AT&amp;T, the biggest of the
US telecoms groups. Earlier this month, AT&amp;T applied for a UK telecoms
operator licence.
BT was additionally weakened by news that Mr Barry Romeril, its highly
regarded finance director, is leaving the company to join Xerox Corporation
in the US so close to the sell-off of the government's remaining 21.8 per
cent stake in BT. The share sale is expected in July.
Telecoms analysts were largely unmoved by the AT&amp;T move. 'It is merely part
of the ritual mud-slinging which should continue until AT&amp;T gets reciprocal
access,' said an analyst, who nevertheless expressed surprise and
disappointment at Mr Romeril's departure. 'He always had a high profile in
the City and is seen as largely responsible for the cost-cutting that has
transformed BT,' he added.
BT shares dropped 9 1/2 , or 2.3 per cent, to 406 1/2 p on turnover of 15m,
the highest for more than three months. Cable and Wireless, whose Mercury
telecoms division is thought to be especially vulnerable to the threat of
increased US competition, fell 18 to 684p.
</TEXT>
