<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WILD rumours and technical position-taking combined to ensure an exciting
day in the futures with one of the busiest sessions of late, writes
Christopher Price.
Trading started quietly enough with the June contract opening slightly
firmer at 2,844 and being bought up gently to 2,850 in the first half-hour
of trading. Then, in a mid-morning lull, a very heavy bout of selling began.
This dominated the day's trading in the cash market and sent June sharply
lower.
The instigator of the selling, which was spread across the whole market, was
rumoured to be Mr George Soros, the US trader who controls the influential
Quantum Fund. It was said that the billionaire dealer was selling futures to
pay for his large part-purchase of a gold manufacturer. Other rumours
abounded and with them a variety of other names.
Also, many traders have continued bearish on the short-term outlook for the
FT-SE 100, believing the recovery story to be overdone and the market to
have run ahead of itself. Whatever the reasons, June continued its slide to
reach its low of 2,776 shortly before 2pm. At this time, June was running at
a 15-point discount to the cash market.
A modest rally took June forward to close at 2,792, a slight discount to its
fair value premium of around 6. Volume was a hefty 19,529 lots. Options
trade was also active.
