<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Money Markets: Large repo rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS a strong rise in D-Mark and French franc futures yesterday after
the Bundesbank reduced its repo rate by more than the market had expected,
writes James Blitz.
The Bundesbank cut the repo rate - which sets the cost of lending
short-dated funds to commercial banks - from 8.09 per cent to 7.75 per cent.
Some dealers were impressed that the repo rate cut was greater than last
week's 25 basis points lowering of the discount rate to 7.25 per cent.
The repo reduction forced the June contract up to a high of 92.80 from a
previous 92.70. The September contract was up on even heavier volume, from a
previous close of 93.55 to a high of 93.65.
However, the contracts later fell back as the German bund market declined on
fears that easier monetary policy would lead to higher inflation.
A dealer recalled that Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the Bundesbank president, had
said that the central bank would look at the long end of the market when
planning its rate-cutting strategy.
The June contract receded to finish at 92.74 and the September contract at
93.60. German call money closed rather firmer, at around 7.72 per cent,
following a net drain of funds in the Bundesbank's weekly operation.
The repo cut had a more lasting impact on the French franc market, raising
speculation of another easing in France's officially posted interest rates
today.
One-month French francs dropped from about 9.25 per cent to below 8.00 per
cent. Three-month French francs were about 100 basis points lower at one
stage, falling to about 7.80 per cent. The June French franc contract surged
to a close of 92.23 from a previous 91.98.
Sterling futures rose in tandem with Euromarks, with the June contract
peaking 7 basis points higher at 93.97. However, it slipped back to end more
or less unchanged on the day as sterling lost ground against the D-Mark on
the foreign exchanges.
Three-month money closed little changed at 6 1/16 per cent, having been as
low as 6 per cent at one stage. The one-year rate finished slightly higher
at 6 1/4 per cent.
The small shortage of Pounds 600m was partly the cause of the easier cash
situation, pushing the overnight lending rate down to 2 per cent at around
lunchtime.
</TEXT>
