<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Foreign Exchanges: Dollar unmoved by repo cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE D-MARK remained comparatively strong against the dollar and European
currencies yesterday in spite of a larger than expected cut in one of the
Bundesbank's key interest rates, writes James Blitz.
The Bundesbank surprised many dealers by reducing its repo rate - the rate
at which it lends short-term money to commercial banks - from 8.09 per cent
to 7.75 per cent. Market expectations had been for a cut to about 7.90 per
cent.
The size of the easing underlined recent comments from Bundesbank officials
that inflation is no longer as big a problem as had been perceived, and that
the central bank is trying to test how far it can ease monetary policy.
Mr Gerald Holtham, chief economist at Lehman Brothers in London, said the
cut in the repo rate had brought the cost of money market funds in line with
the new discount rate level. He believes there will be speculation of
another easing in the Bundesbank's rate floor before its next council
meeting in a week's time.
However, the repo rate cut failed to give the dollar much relief after its
recent fall against the D-Mark. After closing at DM1.5847 at the end of
trading in New York on Tuesday, the US currency peaked at DM1.5930 in
Europe. But it later fell back to end at DM1.5860. In New York yesterday it
finished at DM1.5799.
The dollar's performance seems rather lame, considering that it has been
supported in the last two days by a generous cut in German rates and by
Federal Reserve intervention to support the US currency against the yen.
The dollar closed stronger against the yen in London at Y112.5, up from
Y111.2, and in New York ended at Y112.1. But there are signs the currency
remains hampered by uncertainty over US growth prospects and the direction
of President Clinton's administration.
Mr Mark Austin, an economist at Midland Global Markets in London, believes
that a worse than expected figure for first-quarter GDP in the US today
might also provide a setback for the dollar.
Most European currencies were stronger against the D-Mark in the European
morning but later fell back. Sterling again broke the DM2.50 level, but
subsequently declined to close unchanged at DM2.4925.
At least one dealer said the Bank of England was in the market, selling the
pound in order to replenish its foreign reserves.
The French franc was firmer amid speculation that the Bundesbank cut had
made an easing in French official rates more likely. The franc ended
fractionally up at FFr3.374 to the D-Mark.
The one currency to strengthen markedly in the last two days has been the
Spanish peseta, helped by more Bank of Spain intervention. The peseta closed
at Pta73.07 per D-Mark from a previous Pta73.68. It also moved up from
bottom place in the exchange rate mechanism's grid to third from bottom.
</TEXT>
