<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Baden-Wuerttemberg (9): Crossroads to everywhere -
Mannheim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANS usually describe their extensive motorways and railways with a touch
of national pride.
In Mannheim, they praise them as the key to the city's success, writes
ARIANE GENILLARD.
Every day 140 inter-city expresses go through its main railway station; it
is 40 minutes from Frankfurt airport, and the trains go on to Munich,
Stuttgart or Nuremberg. And, say local officials, its rents are 30 per cent
cheaper than in Frankfurt.
The local economic development office wants to promote Mannheim as an
attractive location for foreign and domestic businessmen. It hopes that it
will soon rival Frankfurt as a leading business and financial centre.
Located where three Lander meet, Mannheim is the second largest city in
Baden-Wurttemberg.
It has 300,000 inhabitants and there are another 1.5m people in the
surrounding conurbations.
It is traditionally an industrial area but now it is trying to develop
services. In the early 1970s, two-third of its workers were employed by
industry.
Today, industry employs only a third and the others are in services, mostly
banking and insurances.
The city, located on the confluence of the Rhine and the Neckar, has also
become an attractive location for freight business, with nearly 200
transport companies based there. The city also enjoys direct rail services
to Strasbourg, Luxembourg and Switzerland.
Officials hope that the expansion of the services sector, in which 10,000
jobs were created last year, will partially offset the city's 7 per cent
unemployment rate which compares with the average rate in the country.
One of the new arrivals is Quick Controls, a British company selling
computer technology in banking. Mr Ron Jones, chief executive of the UK
parent company, says: 'We chose Mannheim because our operational costs were
significantly cheaper than in Frankfurt. We decided to run our distribution
from Germany rather than England and finally chose Mannheim because it is so
close to Frankfurt.'
On the city outskirts, a huge business centre is under construction. Its
rectilinear lay-out, with lettered and numbered streets crossing each other,
is reminiscent of Manhattan.
Whether the resemblance will grow, remains to be seen.
</TEXT>
