<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Baden-Wuerttemberg (8): Civic pride that survived
the devastation of war - Stuttgart and Karlsruhe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BADEN-WUERTTEMBERG did not come into existence until 1952, created by the
merger of three smaller states occupied after the war by French and US
forces, writes DAVID WALLER.
The state's three largest cities - Stuttgart, Mannheim and Karlsruhe - all
have the distinction of once having been state capitals (of Wurttemberg, the
Palatinate and Baden respectively.) The three towns were bombed heavily
during the war, with the result that little of the historical city-centres
remain. But regional pride - and regional rivalries - are still sharply
defined.
STUTTGART, state capital of Baden-Wurttemberg, is at the heart of what the
locals call Swabia, a region which is more than just the geographical area
of Wurttemberg in the eastern part of the state - or indeed of the ancient
Duchy of Swabia. It also describes a state of mind - one which has helped
Baden-Wurttemberg develop into the prosperous region that it is today.
The Swabians are the Scots of Germany - invariably Protestant, they are
frugal, work hard and like accumulating capital. Gifted engineers and
mechanics, 'they believe that if they should do something they should do it
right,' says Mr Manfred Rommel, Mayor of Stuttgart.
He says that it is no accident that Hegel, the inventor of dialectical
philosophy, was born in the city: 'Swabians have their heads filled with all
sorts of incompatible ideas which they struggle to reconcile with one
another.'
Passionately independent, they also love red-tape which creates a race of
what Rommel calls 'frustrated bureaucrats'.
Today's Swabians may still combine a job in one of the Mercedes factories
with a little vineyard in the hills surrounding Stuttgart. When they have
tired of work they can take advantage of the city's rich cultural life:
Stuttgart's theatres, concert-halls and especially its world-famous ballet
under Marcia Haydee and Richard Cragun are booked out for months in advance.
KARLSRUHE, the former capital of Baden, was founded only in 1715 when a
certain Margrave Charles of Baden-Durlach built a palace there to escape his
wife and entertain his mistresses.
It still retains a relaxed atmosphere, which owes as much to its historical
origins as to its proximity to the French border. After the war it was made
home to Germany's Federal Constitutional Court, but this has not dispelled
resentment toward the state government in Stuttgart.
Karlsruhe likes to see itself as Baden-Wurttemberg's technological centre.
It benefited from the activist investment policies promoted by Mr Lothar
Spath, Baden-Wurttemberg's prime minister until January last year, which
helped to endow it with a wealth of scientific bodies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
