<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Baden-Wuerttemberg (7): Family factories are the
economy's backbone - The central role of the 'Mittelstand'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLING in a wooded valley near Karlsruhe is the main production plant of
Jung Gmbh, a family-owned manufacturer of metal components used primarily by
the German car industry.
The company, founded in 1880, is a classic example of the 'Mittelstand'
business on which the economic success not just of Baden-Wurttemberg but
also of western Germany as a whole is founded.
Employing fewer than 300 people, the company has been through several
revolutions in the 113 years of its existence, and is on the verge of yet
another transformation amid a serious downturn in the car industry where its
main customers are to be found.
It started life as a manufacturer of champagne producing machines. In the
1920s it underwent its first major transformation and was turned into a
manufacturer of thread-cutting calipers and wash presses.
After the war it began producing parts - components used not only by the car
industry but by the building machine, hydraulics, machine-tool, aircraft,
power-plant and other industries.
This - subject to technological modifications to bring the company up to
'world-class' standards in terms of computer-aided manufacturing and
just-in-time deliveries - has been the mainstay of the business until the
present day.
Turnover last year was DM60m. Like much of German industry, Jung thrived on
the boom induced by reunification of the country - and like many much larger
companies it failed to see the signs of impending downturn.
Confidently expecting turnover to climb to DM90m this year, Jung was
planning to double its manufacturing capacity at its main site at
Neuenbuburg. Sheer luck meant that the downturn last autumn arrived before
it started to build the factory. The project was shelved and according to
Ludwig Andra, head of information technology at the factory, turnover is
likely to stay at DM60m again this year.
The company stands on the verge of another major strategic change of
direction. For some years 40 per cent of sales have gone to just one car
manufacturer - and this manufacturer is pressing all its components
suppliers for major cost reduction.
In order to reduce its vulnerability to the cost squeeze, Jung has decided
that in future it will specialise in the assembly of sophisticated products
rather than the simple production of components. For example, it has moved
beyond drilling and milling the case in which a gear box is housed to
producing the entire gear box.
At the same time, Jung has started to pay much more careful attention to its
own costs - something that Andra concedes was never a priority during more
prosperous times.
Jung's experiences reflect a pattern repeated, in one way or another, at
thousands of other companies across Baden-Wurttemberg.
Although Baden-Wurttemberg is known as home to Daimler-Benz, Germany's
largest industrial company, and many other large industrial groups, the
backbone of the local economy is formed by small businesses.
Nearly 60 per cent of all companies in the Land employ fewer than 200 people
and 99.8 per cent employ fewer than 500. Small to medium-sized companies
account for half the state's economic output.
There are around 14,000 small manufacturing companies, and many of these,
like Jung, are exposed to a double burden. They are suffering the brunt of a
domestic and international recession at the same time as facing major
structural change.
Those industrial sectors which face the biggest problems - car component
manufacturers, machine tools - are also those with the biggest concentration
of Mittelstand companies.
Economics suggest many smaller companies will be forced to abandon their
cherished independence as the price of survival under present conditions.
There have already been a large number of mergers and unprecedented
cooperation agreements in, for example, the machine-tool sector suggesting
that this process is already well underway.
Dire prognostications of crisis in the Mittelstand ignore some of the
advantages enjoyed by Germany's medium-sized businesses.
While many of Germany's larger companies have lost touch with their
entrepreneurial roots and acquired a bureaucratic culture, the Mittelstand
is highly entrepreneurial and imaginative. Notwithstanding developments in
the world economy over which managers have no control, the smaller companies
have the flexibility to adapt to changed circumstances - as Jung is hoping
to do with its move towards higher value-added components assembly.
Another point is that many of Baden-Wurttemberg's smaller companies occupy
unusual market niches which leave them relatively immune to the downturn in
so many industrial sectors.
The business owned by Hans-Peter Stihl and his family is a classic example
of this. The Andreas Stihl group, based at Waiblingen near Stuttgart, is one
of the world's leading manufacturers of chain- and other forms of
motor-powered saws. The business, founded in 1926 and with nearly 5,500
employees worldwide, has a 30 per cent share of the world market in such
saws. Turnover last year was DM1.2bn.
Mr Stihl, who is head of the pan-German chamber of commerce (IHK), says that
the biggest problem facing Mittelstand companies in Baden-Wurttemberg, as
elsewhere in Germany, is the level of costs, particularly wage-costs. He
voices the familiar complaint that wages climbed at a far higher rate than
productivity in recent years.
While Stihl's earnings are under pressure because of wage costs, the impact
is mitigated because a considerable proportion of the group's manufacturing
is done outside Germany. 'We had the foresight to set up manufacturing plant
abroad as long ago as 1976,' says Stihl. Some 2,500 of the group's employees
work outside Germany.
Stihl's company has grown beyond the scope of the typical Schwabisch small
family business. He is confident that the bulk of smaller Baden-Wurttemberg
businesses 'are able to make the necessary adjustment' to present
conditions, mainly by lopping costs. He believes that the Mittelstand will
emerge on the other side of recession and structural change leaner and
fitter than it was before.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Jung.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3714 Motor Vehicle Parts and Accessories.
</IN>
