<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Baden-Wuerttemberg (3): Heavyweight feels the pain
of recession - The problems of Germany's leading industrial company / The
importance of being Daimler-Ben
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF the company's own forecasts are realised, Daimler-Benz this year will
generate around DM1bn profit - almost exactly the same as it did a decade
ago when it was a simple automotive company, with sales of DM44bn. Now it is
a 'technology group', turning over almost DM100bn.
Since 1984 the pride of Baden-Wurttemberg has ballooned into Germany's
biggest industrial company. As well as Mercedes-Benz it has grown to embrace
Deutsche Aerospace (Dasa), the AEG electrical and electronic engineering
business and Debis, a software and financial services business.
From a peak of DM1.9bn in the boom year of 1991, net earnings fell 25 per
cent last year and are sliding towards DM1bn in 1993. The faithful milch cow
Mercedes, which usually accounts for two-thirds of group profits, will this
year produce around 85 per cent of the total.
The failure of Daimler's management to generate consistent and worthwhile
profit gains from its expensive and showy expansion programme has brought it
under persistent and increasingly critical fire from media and city critics.
Chairman Edzard Reuter, who has borne the brunt of most of the criticism,
bristles visibly every time the subject comes up. 'We never said the
importance of the automotive business would decline in the context of the
group before the end of the century,' he says.
And he rattles off the special circumstances which have come to haunt
Daimler - and much of the rest of German industry - since the easy days of
the 1980s. Global recession, monetary upheavals and the economic disorder
following the dismantling of the Iron Curtain and the Soviet empire were not
allowed for in Daimler's grand strategy.
'I must confess that we did not foresee the collapse of communism,' he says,
with more than a tinge of irony. The end of the cold war severely buckled
one of Daimler's new legs, the defence business of Deutsche Aerospace. This
year alone, German government spending cuts will cost Dasa around DM1bn in
lost sales.
'If the defence cuts had not happened Deutsche Aerospace (which lost DM340m
on DM17bn sales last year) would be highly profitable by now,' Reuter
claims.
Even so, he is convinced he has built up a potential-packed aircraft and
space technology business. 'Just look back at the state of aerospace in
Germany when we started ..it was fragmented, non-existent as a force in
world markets. We have reorganised it and it is now respected worldwide,' he
says. Dasa includes Dornier, the MTU engines business, Germany's European
Airbus stake and now Fokker of the Netherlands.
Putting on a brave face, Reuter points out that military work accounts for
only around 8 per cent of Daimler's group business. But defence spending
cuts have not just affected Dasa's sales and profits, the marked reduction
in government and corporate involvement in military research has blunted the
leading-edge of the group's technological and materials R&amp;D crucial to civil
aerospace activities and important to other group activities in vehicles and
engineering.
Meanwhile, AEG, which encompasses washing machines, automation technology
and railways, continues to stumble. After a DM624m loss in 1991, it squeezed
a DM10m profit out of DM11bn sales last year, and is now on the way back
into the red, according to chairman Georg Stockl.
Edzard Reuter is prepared now to concede that AEG may have waited too long
before last year's decision to cast out the prime loss-maker, the historic
Olympia office equipment subsidiary which was simply smothered by
competition from the far east.
Originally a typewriter manufacturer, Olympia is a classic case of a
traditional German company which failed to make the grade in high-tech
global markets. As such it is seen by Daimler's bitterest critics as a model
for the whole group.
Daimler based its entire diversification strategy on the need to break out
of the relatively narrow and crowded confines of the automotive business.
Now it has fallen to the car makers at Mercedes to show the way ahead for
the rest of the business and at the same time generate the cash needed to
support structural change elsewhere.
Driven out of its ivory tower by keen competition, the company has
undertaken an extraordinary reversal of its most ingrained traditions. Gone
is the notion that Mercedes keeps strictly to the market for sedate,
heavyweight executive saloons. Gone too is the idea that the company's cars
can only be manufactured in Germany. A family-style van is to be built in
Barcelona; a 'fun car' will be made in the US, and a pocket-sized city
vehicle will follow, also likely to be built outside Germany.
The engineering elite, who once dominated the business, have been integrated
as members of countless management, design and manufacturing teams. Price,
once discussed as an afterthought after the engineers had dictated the form
and content of each model, is now the starting point of all development
plans.
Product prices are established according to what the market will bear, what
the competition is offering in a comparable market sector, and what the
company can accept as a reasonable profit. Then project teams are required
to deliver components, processes - and finished vehicle - according to fixed
targets.
This programme has led to the greater use of bought-in parts, while speedier
and therefore cheaper production methods have reduced the time taken to
build a car from 45 man-hours to 35. So far, the Japanese competition's cost
advantages have been cut from 35 per cent to 15 per cent, production
executives claim.
The first fruits of this revolutionary change of attitude and methods will
be yielded this summer when Mercedes launches a replacement for its 10
year-old compact 190 series.
To judge by outward appearances the new C-class is a classic, traditional
Mercedes car. But the bodywork conceals radical differences. The company
claims the new vehicle is packed with 20 per cent more customer value than
the old model, while the price will be basically unchanged.
At the bottom-line, lean production on this scale means ever-leaner
payrolls. Although the effects of recession have blurred the picture, many
of the cost-savings made to improve the company's competitiveness have been
made at the expense of the workforce. Almost 15,000 of the 18,000 group jobs
which went last year were lost at Mercedes. The automotive business will
cast off at least another 7,000 this year, while other divisions shed 8,000.
Meanwhile, most new jobs, which in the past would have been filled by German
workers, are being created overseas. Those involved in the manufacture of
Mercedes' planned new models will benefit Spain and the US in the first
instance.
The company is also discussing assembly in Mexico, South Korea and the
Philippines, and is in the early planning stages of a projected car assembly
factory in India.
</TEXT>
