<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Fear of LME scuppered US merger
 -The abandonment of a planned market marriage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREAT of surging volume growth at the London Metals Exchange, and the
perception that the UK's commodities trading regulations are less
restrictive than those in the US, were the primary reasons why the Chicago
Board of Trade, the world's largest futures exchange, decided against
acquiring New York's Commodity Exchange (Comex), the LME's chief rival, says
Mr Patrick Arbor, the CBoT chairman.
'The UK regulatory environment is more conducive to growth,' said Mr Arbor.
'Take a look at the growth of the LME and the International Petroleum
Exchange, relative to the Comex and the New York Mercantile Exchange. We
think that has something to do with the regulatory operating environment.'
Mr Arbor complains that compared to London, the paperwork required for
opening customer accounts in the US is prohibitive, that more compliance
people are required, and that in general 'the London regulatory environment
is a lot more liberal, less constrictive, and less costly'.
The LME's market share and its comparative regulatory advantage raised
questions about the cost-savings expected from the CBoT/Comex merger, Mr
Arbor said. A CBoT committee last week recommended that the merger, which
had been unpopular with Comex members, be abandoned. The Comex is currently
considering a takeover plan from its neighbour the Nymex.
LME volume grew by 46 per cent last year to 24.7m contracts. Comex, in
contrast, saw a 16 per cent drop in volume last year, to 12.7m contracts. In
the energy sector, Nymex had volume of 47.2m contracts, a 16 per cent gain
over 1991, while London's IPE saw growth of 26 per cent, to 10.7m contracts.
The Comex trades primarily precious metals, while the LME specialises in
base metals. Their two product lines overlap, however, with high grade
copper. In copper, the LME has by far the dominant market share.
Mr Arbor said the regulatory discrepancies and their impact on the Comex's
world competitiveness were brought home when a committee of CBoT accountants
and attorneys reviewed the Comex's books after he and Ms Donna Redel, Comex
chairwoman, signed the merger proposal January 25.
In fact, the relative volume growth at the LME could hardly have been a
surprise to Mr Arbor, since his exchange is keenly conscious of market share
lost overseas. Mr Arbor and other CBoT officials have been vocal critics of
US futures regulation for years, and have frequently led the US futures
industry in drives to defeat legislation it thought would constrain
competition.
In this case Mr Arbor may be using the LME as an example against a Clinton
administration proposal to tax futures transactions. 'If we continue to have
a harsher regulatory environment, and if the 14-cent (per contract)
transaction tax is approved, we risk seeing more and more US business going
overseas,' he said.
The Comex review did expose CBoT management more directly to world
competition that it rarely sees in its own operations. The CBoT's biggest
business is futures and options trading in grain and in US government bonds
and notes. None of those products have serious global competition.
While some small grain contracts, most notably in Tokyo and Paris, have
sprung up in recent years, none can compare with the size of the US market,
either in futures volume or in grain production. Gold and silver, the
Comex's major products, are more generic and thus more vulnerable to
competing interests, Mr Arbor says.
In fact, data provided by the US Futures Industry Association show that in
pure volume terms, Comex gold futures volume took a back seat to the upstart
BM &amp; F exchange in Brazil last year. Brazilian gold options jumped to second
place in world metals contract rankings in 1992, with volume at 8m
contracts, while Comex gold futures fell from second to fourth, at 6m.
The LME took first and third place in the rankings, with its aluminium and
copper futures. The volume rankings are deceptive because contract size
varies, and a single Comex gold future represents almost ten times as much
gold as a Brazilian gold option. Still, competitive pressures remain as
trading interest grows outside the US.
US futures industry officials have said that the rational response to those
pressures is to cut costs. After significant consolidation of futures
brokerage firms in the 1980s, they expected to see similar rationalisation
among US exchanges in this decade. The Comex's quest for an operating
partner is just the beginning of that movement, they say.
</TEXT>
<XX>
