<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Australia halts sales from wool
stockpile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Australian government yesterday announced a 12-month moratorium on sales
from the wool industry's 3.9bn-bale stockpile in an attempt to end a slide
in prices, which have already fallen to historic lows.
Mr Simon Crean, primary industries minister, also announced a ADollars 50m
(Pounds 23m) assistance package designed to subsidise debt interest payments
by about 6,500 farmers hit by falling prices and severe drought.
The minister said the postponement of sales from the wool stockpile would
remove the speculative pressure that had contributed a fall in the national
wool indicator from ADollars 5.50 a kilogram in November to ADollars 3.96 on
Friday. The market indicator, a weighted average of auction prices for 15
grades of wool, stood at ADollars 7.29 before the abolition of the wool
industry's ADollars 7 floor price two years ago.
The government's seven-year debt guarantee to the Australian Wool
Realisation Commission, the statutory authority which markets the stockpile,
would be extended by a year, Mr Crean said, and there would be a three-month
review of the wool industry's organisation and structure, to be chaired by
Mr Ross Garnaut, professor of economics at the Australian National
University.
Mr Crean rejected a call by the Australian Wool Council, the main growers'
body, for a cut in the 8.5 per cent wool tax, which finances the stockpile
and the industry's marketing efforts.
'What we are not going to do is to allow the growers. . . to get out of the
obligation they have to meet the debt,' he said. 'We are prepared to support
them in meeting it in a managed way, but they can't have the luxury of
finding some new crisis (each year) and in the end saying to the government:
'you have got to pay the bill'.'
The series of announcements was welcomed by some farmers' associations; the
Queensland Graingrowers Association said the drought package would help
farmers to stay on the land until the rains came. But Mr Alan Bowman,
president of the Wool Council, said the government's decision not to reduce
the wool tax was 'bloody hopeless'. He said the cut 'would have allowed the
industry to help itself.' The Wool Council was also disappointed that the
seven-year disposal schedule for the stockpile had not been extended
indefinitely.
The minister said that Mr Garnaut's review of the industry would consider
fresh marketing initiatives to divert the stockpile sales to non-traditional
buyers of wool, which could help to ease pressure on auction prices.
One of the ideas being considered by officials is the use of wool as an
insulation material in the construction industry. The government is also
considering proposals to exchange wool for equity in Russian textile mills.
</TEXT>
