<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: EC expected to lift meat import
ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Commission is expected to lift its ban on imports of meat and
dairy products from Central and East Europe today, but controls are likely
to remain on livestock from Poland and Croatia.
The European Community has been negotiating with 18 eastern European states
to produce tighter controls on export certificates following a
foot-and-mouth scare in Italy.
Most have responded with new controls, but Poland is understood to have
voiced reservations about the EC's request to impose a 14-day quarantine on
live animals.
EC officials said yesterday that restrictions on Polish dairy imports would
be lifted, while the ban on Croatian imports would continue because of
concern about the effectiveness of local controls. EC farm ministers have
failed to agree farm prices and milk quotas for 1993-94 despite a strong
effort by the Danish presidency to reach agreement in Luxembourg. Mr Rene
Steichen, EC farm commissioner, criticising the Danish package as too
generous, urged a more modest settlement.
