<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER'S renewed fall early yesterday on the LME destroyed the confidence
which had been seeping into other base metals after copper's relative
stability over the past few days. Three-month copper fell nearly Dollars 30
in morning pre-market trading to around Dollars 1,885 a tonne as
option-related selling, liquidation and Chinese sales touched off sell
stops. For the rest of the day the price held in a narrow range, closing at
Dollars 1,891. But the damage had already been done to other metals where
long positions taken on recent strength were quickly disposed of. London's
robusta COFFEE futures closed lower as New York ran into a bout of profit
taking after the May contract's advance of more than 6 cents a lb over the
previous two days. Dealers said a modest setback was to be expected given
the magnitude of the preceding gains. Constructive short-term charts
remained the main supportive influence, with fundamentals still considered
fairly bearish. GOLD closed higher on the London bullion market after fixing
below Dollars 350 a troy ounce.
Compiled from Reuters
