<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Brighter prospects seen for
silver
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SILVER SHOULD benefit from the present positive sentiment in the gold
market, according to the American Precious Metals Advisors consultancy
organisation. It suggests silver's price this year should average more than
USDollars 4 a troy ounce and reach Dollars 4.40 to Dollars 4.60 by the
year-end compared with Dollars 3.95 in 1992.
'Psychology is particularly important for silver because of the large stocks
of this metal that overhang the market and the readiness of holders to part
with silver,' says Mr Jeffrey Nichols, president of APMA, in his latest
MetalsFax publication.
He suggests that liquid silver stocks may amount to 2bn ounces in North
America and western Europe - enough to satisfy demand for more than three
years - and many investors, particularly those in the US, bought their metal
at prices well above the present levels.
'Years of persistently declining prices have made it especially difficult
for silver to manage a sustainable recovery because many holders at first
will use any rally as an opportunity to unload,' he adds.
APMA believes the silver market will see its fourth annual supply deficit in
1993 with demand outpacing production by nearly 81m ounces. This compares
with a 1992 deficit of 46m ounces.
Fabrication demand is forecast to rise from 574m to 580m ounces mainly
because of record usage by the photographic industry, already the biggest
user of silver. APMA forecasts the photographic industry, spurred on by the
lowest real silver prices since the early 1970s and growth in picture-taking
in the emerging industrial countries, will use 210m ounces in 1993, up from
207m in each of the past two years.
APMA predicts a recovery in Indian imports following liberalisation of
government regulations so that non-residents can take 3,200 ounces of silver
into the country,subject to a 50 cents-an-ounce duty.
Mr Nichols points out that between 75 and 80 per cent of silver is mined as
a by-product of other metal mining. He predicts mine production this year
outside the former eastern bloc countries is likely to fall by 8m ounces
from the 1992 level to 352m ounces. Supplies of secondary or scrap silver
are also expected to fall, from 196m to 194m ounces.
MetalsFax: Dollars 6,000 a year from APMA in the US on fax 802 860 7596
