<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Banana islands aim to calm US
'hostility'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE POLITICAL leaders of Caribbean banana producing countries are to meet US
trade officials next month in an attempt to dispel what the leaders say is
Washington's 'hostility' to the new European Community regime for importing
the fruit.
Mr John Compton, the prime minister of St Lucia, said he and his colleagues
from St Vincent, Dominica and Grenada, will meet the US trade representative
to discuss the US attitude, which he said threatened the economic foundation
of the four islands.
The four, which make up the Windward group, and other producers of the
African, Caribbean and Pacific group, are seeking protection for their
market share in Europe, and fear competition from cheaper Latin American
fruit.
The EC's agriculture ministers have proposed that from July there will be a
2m tonnes-a-year quota for Latin American fruit and that this will attract
duty of Ecu100 (Pounds 78) a tonne. Imports of Latin American fruit above
this level will attract a duty of Ecu850 a tonne. Caribbean and other
traditional suppliers, such as those in Africa, will have access for the
remainder of the EC's needs, which traders say is about 1.5m tonnes a year.
This fruit will pay no tariff.
The new regime has been criticised by the US and by the Latin American
countries.
In a statement to St Lucia's parliament, Mr Compton said that the US
position on the issue showed that the Clinton administration was 'even more
unsympathetic' to the EC's proposed regime than was the Bush administration.
</TEXT>
