<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Government Bonds: Disappointing result to Bank of England
Pounds 3bn auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government bond market tumbled on disappointment over the results of
the Bank of England's Pounds 3bn gilt auction.
The auction of 7 1/4 per cent stock due 1998 was covered only 1.77 times by
bids totalling Pounds 5.3bn, with foreign demand failing to reach the levels
expected.
The average yield was 6.98 per cent with a tail - the difference between the
average and maximum yield - of 1 basis point.
Optimism ahead of the auction had been such that forecasts of cover had
ranged as high as three times, although the low end of the range was 1.5
times.
With overseas investors building up exposure to the strengthening pound
ahead of the auction, some economists believed the optimism on demand
overdone, particularly in view of the cash-flow squeeze on institutions.
The yield curve steepened as prices fell by more than a point on gilts with
maturities over 15 years.
The June gilt future fell through a key support level of 104.31 to touch a
low of 104.20. Rising concern about inflation was one of the factors making
the long end vulnerable.
THE German government bond market opened at a high level in anticipation of
the Bundesbank cutting the repo rate. It rose a little more when the cut
surpassed expectations, but profit-taking led the market down thereafter.
The repo was cut from 8.09 per cent to 7.75 per cent, 10 to 15 basis points
less than typical forecasts.
The June bund contract opened at 95.52 and hit 95.60 after the repo news
came through.
It ended at 95.07 after falling through the 95 barrier. Volume was heavy
with 100,000 contracts traded.
As the cost of funding comes down at the short end of the market, the yield
curve is normalising.
One of the factors turning it more positive is a looming supply of 10-year
bonds as public sector debt levels grow.
FRANCE also took further steps towards a positively sloping yield curve.
Yields on two-year stock have fallen below those on five years as investor
interest concentrates on the short end of the market.
Conditions seemed favourable for further cuts in French interest rates with
overnight money quoted at 8.70 per cent, 30 basis points below the middle
level between the two official rates.
THE dollar's rally against the yen helped push the Japanese government bond
market down further.
The June futures contract opened a point lower in Tokyo, at 107.90, in
response to the weakening of the yen against the dollar and to the fall in
US Treasury prices.
By the close in Tokyo, another 30 basis points had been shed from the
futures contract to give 107.60 and the low of 107.48 breached the 107.50
support level.
The No 145 cash bond due 2002 opened at a higher yield of 4.335 per cent and
weakened to 4.42 per cent at the close.
The yen's decline joined the buoyant Nikkei stock market index, which again
closed above 20,000, in removing last week's twin drivers of the bond
market.
Concern about economic recovery was stirred up by Tuesday's sharp
improvement in the index of leading economic indicators.
Nervousness was amplified, however, by the onset of the Golden Week
holidays, which start today and will create a bit of a vacuum until the end
of next week.
US TREASURY prices were mixed in light trading yesterday after a successful
auction of Dollars 11bn in five-year notes.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  3/32 at 102
19/32 , yielding 6.915 per cent. At the short end of the market, the
two-year note was slightly firmer, up  1/32 at 100, to yield 3.859 per cent.
Although prices firmed overnight after Tokyo funds bought Treasuries with
the dollars they had acquired from the Japanese central bank, which had
intervened in the foreign exchange markets to help buoy the US currency
against the soaring yen, there was no follow-through when trading opened in
New York.
Following Tuesday's disappointing two-year auction, which left dealers
holding much of the new inventory, the market was apprehensive ahead of the
Dollars 11bn five-year sale.
Dealers feared that the lack of demand which sunk the two-year auction would
do the same for the five-year.
Some analysts noted, however, that the decline in prices that followed
Tuesday's auction could help spur demand for the five-year sale. This
analysis subsequently proved right. Demand for the issue was strong,
although the success of the auction failed to lift longer-dated prices.
</TEXT>
