<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Capital Markets: South Korean securities firms
return to profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON and AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMBINED net profits of South Korea's 32 securities firms jumped to
Won451.7bn (Dollars 570m) in the year to March from Won15.8bn in the
previous year as the Seoul bourse posted its first sustained recovery in
three years, the Securities Supervisory Board said.
All the firms reported profits during the year. In contrast, 10 of them,
including six of the seven leaders, had losses in fiscal 1991.
The general index of the Seoul bourse rose by almost 10 per cent during
1992-93, while trading volume rose by 50 per cent. Increased bond
transactions also contributed to higher profits.
Daewoo Securities was the most profitable with a Won57.1bn surplus, against
Won10bn the year before.
It was followed by Lucky Securities with Won44.1bn against a loss of
Won2.5bn and Dongsuh Securities with Won40.1bn against a loss of Won5.8bn.
Jardine Fleming has opened its first office in Pakistan, AP-DJ reports. The
merchant banking arm of Jardine Matheson group said the office, based in
Lahore, would provide fundamental research on companies listed on the stock
exchanges of Karachi and Lahore. Jardine Fleming hopes to expand to other
securities-related activities in Pakistan in due course.
Alan Smith, managing director of Jardine Fleming in Hong Kong, is confident
of Pakistan's long-term outlook for international investors, citing the
country's potential for widespread privatisation of nationalised
enterprises.
The new establishment brings the number of Jardine Fleming offices
throughout the Asia-Pacific region to 16.
