<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Bonds: Kingdom of Sweden back with FFr3bn
issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Kingdom of Sweden returned to the Eurobond market yesterday with a
FFr3bn seven-year issue, the latest borrower to tap the popular French franc
sector.
Borrowers have flocked to the Euro-French franc sector since the
centre-right parties swept to victory at last month's general election. The
result lent support to the French currency, enabling the Bank of France to
lower interest rates - helped by the Bundesbank's recent easing of German
key interest rates.
Although there has already been a lot of new supply in the French franc
sector, the Swedish National Debt Office pointed out that the seven-year
area has been left alone. 'We saw that there was good investor demand in the
seven-year area, and that suited us from our portfolio perspective,' said Ms
Christine Holm, a director of the office.
BNP, the lead manager, added that the seven-year maturity also provided one
of the best maturities for swapping. Part of the proceeds will be swapped,
probably into floating-rate francs.
The bond, which has a coupon of 7.25 per cent, was launched with a spread of
35 basis points over the relevant US Treasury bond, but widened to 36.5
basis points. So far this year, Sweden has borrowed the equivalent of
SKr65bn in the Eurobond market.
Rumours circulated that the Kingdom of Spain may also tap the French franc
sector when it makes the second of its proposed three or four Eurobond
offerings this year. However, an official at the Spanish Treasury said a
firm decision has not yet been taken on the currency front, and that both
Euro-sterling and Euro-French francs are under consideration.
In the dollar sector, the Republic of Colombia launched its much-marketed
Dollars 125m five-year deal at a spread of 215 basis points over the
five-year US Treasury bond. The spread tightened to 205 basis points,
reflecting good demand for the issue.
The proceeds from the bond, which carries a 7 1/8 per cent coupon, will be
used to repay more expensive debt. Colombia lacks a credit rating at the
moment, but Bankers Trust, the lead manager for the deal, said discussions
with Standard &amp; Poor's rating agency are due to take place next week and
they are predicting that a BBB rating will be assigned to the borrower.
</TEXT>
