<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: OMV recovery gives hope for
return to profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OMV, the troubled Austrian integrated oil and chemical group, reports a 1992
net loss of Sch264.5m (Dollars 23.8m), somewhat less than the Sch300m
forecast in January. In 1991, the group made a net profit of Sch1.72bn.
The recovery trend has continued into the first quarter of 1993, with a loss
of Sch125m comparing with a Sch247m deficit in the same 1992 period.
Mr Richard Schenz, who became president last summer following the sudden
resignation of Mr Siegfried Meysel, said there was evidence of some
improvement in the group's markets, and he hoped for a return to modest
profits for the year as a whole.
The directors were meanwhile concentrating on cutting costs. The dividend
for 1992 would be cut from Sch20 per share to Sch15 and capital spending
this year would be reduced from Sch6bn last year to Sch4bn.
Group sales last year were flat at just under Sch83bn, with sales in the
integrated oil and gas businesses up 2.7 per cent to Sch67.1bn, while
chemical sales were down 7.7 per cent to Sch8.37bn and plastics revenues
plunged 14.1 per cent to Sch7.37bn.
A divisional breakdown of after-tax results showed the exploration and
production division moved from a Sch390m loss to a Sch310m profit, while the
gas division raised its profit from Sch1.34bn to Sch1.53bn.
OMV said its selling memorandum for prospective strategic shareholders would
be ready by mid-May. The Austrian state industrial holding company, OIAG,
intends to sell part of its 72 per cent stake, and OMV has said it would
like to have two or three strategic shareholders with 10 to 20 per cent
stakes.
Potential candidates include governments of oil and gas-producing countries
and international oil companies. Mr Wolfgang Ruttenstorfer, finance
director, said he hoped the selection process, in which OMV is being advised
by Lehman Brothers, could be completed by year-end.
