PanCanadian, owned 87 per cent by CP, has reported first-quarter profit of
CDollars 61.3m (USDollars 48.6m), or 49 cents a share, treble the
year-earlier profit of CDollars 20.5m, or 16 cents. Revenues were CDollars
266m, up 33 per cent.
Based on the improved results, the company is hoisting its quarterly
dividend by 5 cents to 20 cents a share.
Oil prices rose 8 per cent and conventional production was up 27 per cent to
84,258 barrels daily. Synthetic crude also fetched higher prices.
PanCanadian is a leading natural gas producer in Alberta and British
Columbia, and shipments and prices were also up sharply.
Demand in Canada and the US, with the long, severe winter, has left some
producers short of contracted volumes, sending them to the spot market for
supplies.
For the whole of 1992, oil production rose 23 per cent and gas sales 29 per
cent. Mr David O'Brien, chairman, says PanCanadian can maintain the momentum
over the next two years because of heavy investment in production and
development.
