<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: Two Japanese banks warn of
losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO of Japan's sickest regional banks, Hyogo and Taiheiyo, yesterday warned
of losses for the year to March.
Hyogo Bank, which earlier this week announced the resignations of five
executives, expects a loss of Y31.7bn (Dollars 285m) for the year, up from
an earlier estimated loss of Y9bn, due to write-offs of bad loans and a
Y10.8bn appraisal loss on securities holdings.
A former director-general of the finance ministry's banking bureau, Mr
Masateru Yoshida, has just been appointed president of the bank, one of the
most prominent victims of the late-1980s, when it and several affiliates
were big lenders to the property market.
Hyogo is attempting to support 10 finance affiliates with Y1,600bn in
outstanding loans, of which an increasing percentage are bad. The bank will
take a special charge of Y29.6bn to assist in the rehabilitation of those
affiliates.
Taiheiyo Bank, based in Tokyo, is being restructured by four commercial
banks which have pumped in about Y60bn in loans. However, the bank is still
expecting a loss of Y1.96bn for the year, as the continuing fall in property
prices has slowed the recovery of debts.
Like Hyogo, Taiheiyo has apparently boosted profits by selling branches, but
the success of the restructuring, scheduled to last for 10 years, will
depend on a recovery in the property market.
The full extent of the non-performing loan burden at the two banks remains
unclear, as they have been forced to slash interest rates charged to ailing
customers, though these reductions do not show up in the official
calculations of non-performing assets.
In contrast, Sumitomo Bank, one of the biggest City banks, signalled that it
believes the banking industry is heading into better times by announcing
that its net profit for 1992-1993 will be Y14bn, up from a
previously-forecast Y12bn.
Sumitomo reported appraisal losses on securities of Y36.8bn, though the loss
would have been larger but for a surge in Tokyo stock prices during March.
The bank also announced that Mr Toshio Morikawa, its vice-president, will be
promoted to president, succeeding Mr Sotoo Tatsumi, who will become
chairman.
</TEXT>
