<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: US broker to sue Kleinwort
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PAINEWEBBER, the Wall Street securities firm, will file a lawsuit against
Kleinwort Benson today, five days after three senior managers of a
PaineWebber asset management unit defected to the UK investment bank,
allegedly with confidential information.
The suit, to be filed in New York by PaineWebber unit Mitchell Hutchins
Institutional Investors, alleges that three former MHII executives conspired
to misappropriate proprietary and confidential information belonging to
MHII, and wrongly provided Kleinwort's US affiliate with that information.
Among other allegations outlined in the suit, PaineWebber charges that the
three executives - former MHII president and chief executive Mr Stephen
Canter, former chief investment officer Mr Emad Zikry, and former
vice-president Mr Thomas Goepfert - solicited MHII clients, disparaged MHII,
and solicited MHII employees to join them at Kleinwort Benson International
Investment, the London bank's US subsidiary. Ultimately, seven other MHII
employees left to join Kleinwort.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages from Kleinwort, and an injunction from
the court barring the defendants from soliciting or accepting asset
management business from MHII clients, from using MHII information, from
soliciting MHII employees and disparaging the company.
PaineWebber will also ask the court to set up a trust to hold any fees
earned by the defendants from their activities related to MHII.
Today's actions follow last Friday's defection by the three MHII executives,
who helped manage Dollars 4bn of clients fixed-income investments.
PaineWebber says that by Saturday the three had already begun contacting
MHII clients, writing to them on Kleinwort letter-headed paper.
Officers at Kleinwort Benson's New York office were unavailable for comment
last night.
</TEXT>
