<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: Amdahl cuts payout after heavy
shortfall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMDAHL, the US mainframe computer manufacturer, reported heavy first-quarter
losses, including charges associated with job cuts. Last week the company
said it planned to reduce its 8,500 workforce by about 1,000.
Yesterday, the company also announced it had cut its annual dividend from 10
cents a share to 5 cents.
Net losses for the quarter were Dollars 239.7m, or Dollars 2.12 a share,
after a Dollars 243m pre-tax restructuring charge. In 1992, first-quarter
income was Dollars 4.4m, or 4 cents. Revenues declined to Dollars 380.7m
from Dollars 498m.
The company said savings from cutbacks would be substantial and the
streamlining of operations would enable it to eliminate some excess
production capacity within the mainframe computer industry. This should
stabilise prices and profit margins.
Amdahl warned last month that first-quarter losses would be larger than
analysts had expected and revenues would be below expectations.
The company said soft economic conditions have produced erratic demand and
intense competitive pressure on prices.
The first quarter is also generally the weakest in the mainframe computer
market. This one was unusually difficult because of announcements of new
mainframe computers made in February by both Amdahl and IBM. Customers
typically await such announcements before making purchase decisions.
'We remain committed to the IBM-compatible mainframe market,' said Mr Joseph
Zemke, president and chief executive officer. 'But we also recognise that
growth has slowed down as customers investigate smaller systems that appear
to offer lower computing costs.'
But he remained convinced that customers would ultimately recognise the need
for mainframe computers.
</TEXT>
