<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: Carbide ahead in cost-cutting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNION Carbide, the US chemicals group, yesterday said it was more than a
year ahead of schedule in its efforts to cut annual costs by Dollars 400m.
Mr Robert Kennedy, Carbide's chairman, said: 'Our workforce is slashing
costs and improving operations so dramatically that we now expect to achieve
our goal during 1993.'
The company also posted essentially flat first-quarter 1993 earnings from
continuing operations of Dollars 42m, or 28 cents a share, on sales of
Dollars 1.19bn.
Although the results were in line with the company's forecasts, released
last week, shares in Union Carbide slipped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 19 1/2 at
mid-day in New York.
Analysts had predicted underlying profits of about 19 cents a share for the
group before Union Carbide said its earnings would exceed most estimates.
During the latest quarter, pre-tax earnings from continuing operations
slipped to Dollars 60m from Dollars 69m a year earlier.
In the first three months of 1992, the company had after-tax earnings of
Dollars 42m, or 27 cents, on sales of Dollars 1.19bn, excluding charges for
accounting changes.
Including the income from discontinued operations and after-tax charges for
accounting changes, Union Carbide posted a net loss of Dollars 286m, or
Dollars 2.28, a year ago.
Mr Kennedy said earnings were helped by improving volumes and cost
containment measures, which helped offset lower variable margins for many
products.
The company expects continued pressure on margins and general economic
weakness, especially in overseas markets.
</TEXT>
