<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / International Company News: European operations fall into
loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD'S European automotive operations, including Jaguar, the UK luxury car
maker, registered a net loss of Dollars 82m in the first quarter of 1993
compared with a net profit of Dollars 84m in the corresponding period a year
ago.
Excluding Jaguar, Ford of Europe net profits plunged by 92.3 per cent to
only Dollars 19m in the first quarter from Dollars 246m a year earlier,
chiefly under the the impact of a precipitous fall in new car sales in west
Europe.
New car demand in west Europe in the first three months fell by around 17
per cent to 3.06m, according to industry estimates. Ford forecast yesterday
a fall of 12 per cent for the full year.
Ford vehicle sales in Europe, at 436,122 in the first quarter, were 13 per
cent lower than a year ago.
Ford said that its European financial performance had also been hit by
unfavourable exchange rate movements - in particular between the lira and
the D-Mark - which had reduced pre-tax profits by around Dollars 100m, and
by heavy product launch costs for the new Mondeo family car, which has
replaced the Sierra.
The US carmaker said that Jaguar had reduced its losses in the first quarter
by 40 per cent to Dollars 56m from Dollars 93m a year ago due to increased
sales volumes, in particular in the US.
Jaguar sales rose by 16 per cent year-on-year in the first quarter to 6,374,
helped by a 29 per cent rise in the US to 2,561, and increases in Germany,
Switzerland, the UK and Belgium.
Ford's European automotive operations also took a charge in the first
quarter of Dollars 45m for interest and goodwill write-offs arising from its
1989 takeover of Jaguar.
Ford, which suffered a record loss last year of Dollars 1.3bn on its
European automotive operations, said that its objective was to break even
this year, excluding Jaguar. This target would be difficult to achieve,
however, if sales continued to fall steeply.
</TEXT>
