<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / UK Company News: Trinity Holdings makes Pounds 7.07m -
Maiden full-year performance slightly above flotation forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRINITY HOLDINGS, the specialist vehicle manufacturer which came to the
market last October, produced maiden pre-tax profits of Pounds 7.07m for the
year to end-January.
The outcome - slightly higher than the flotation forecast - compared with
Pounds 3.39m last time.
Earnings per share of 10.7p, against 5.2p, provided ample cover for the
dividend which, as promised, is 1.5p.
Turnover rose 34 per cent to Pounds 109.9m and is expected to rise again in
the current year on the back of, as Mr Geoff Hollyhead, chairman, said, 'a
record order book and with increased registrations in our major markets.'
Although the devaluation of sterling has made Trinity more competitive
overseas - over a third of its output is exported - the rise in turnover
this year will be less marked than during the previous 12 months.
The turnover total included a first-time contribution of Pounds 12.6m from
the acquisitions of Reliance Mercury Vehicles and Carmichael International,
respectively producers of specialist tractors for use in docks and airports
and specialist fire fighting vehicles.
Mr Hollyhead said that Dennis Specialist Vehicles, which is both the largest
division in the group and the leader of the UK bus market, is budgeting for
further growth but not at the same rate as in 1992-93 when sales climbed to
Pounds 48.7m against Pounds 36.9m.
Trinity had cash of Pounds 5.1m at the year-end, the flotation having
cleared borrowings and redeemed the group's preference shares. Of the Pounds
1.42m interest charges, Pounds 1.3m was incurred before flotation.
With this background, the group is looking both to finance organic growth
and to expand through further acquisition.
Noting that opportunities had been examined in both the UK and abroad, Mr
Hollyhead said: 'We are not averse to an overseas manufacturing base,' but
added that Trinity is not prepared to push gearing above 30 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Trinity Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3713 Truck and Bus Bodies.
    P3714 Motor Vehicle Parts and Accessories.
