<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / UK Company News: Stanhope Properties Pounds 15.4m in the red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STANHOPE Properties, the joint owner of the Broadgate complex in the City of
London, yesterday announced a pre-tax loss of Pounds 15.4m for the first
half of 1992, marginally up on the comparative Pounds 15.3m which included
Pounds 1.19m abortive merger costs.
The company also announced that Mr Paul Reichmann, head of Olympia &amp; York,
the crippled property developer that owned a third of Stanhope, had resigned
from the board.
Stanhope said its recovery was largely dependent upon increasing values at
Broadgate, which were likely to benefit from the rising demand from tenants
and investors that stemmed from the fall in interest rates and sterling. 'If
the estimates of future growth projected by leading surveyors are met, the
Broadgate assets will be among the first to benefit,' it said.
However, its optimism was tempered by the difficulties in letting its
unoccupied buildings, including Ludgate, the office complex on the western
edge of the City. 'It would be prudent at this stage to envisage a further
net reduction in the value of the group's property assets,' it said.
Stanhope, which is part of the London regeneration Consortium redeveloping
land around King's Cross, said it would receive compensation if the
government chose to make St Pancras, rather than Kings Cross, the terminus
for the Channel Tunnel Rail Link. The compensation could be worth several
million pounds, it said.
Turnover rose from Pounds 24.3m to Pounds 27.5m. Net interest payable surged
from Pounds 7.85m to Pounds 11.6m, partly as a result of higher average
borrowings and partly of a changed accounting policy. Losses per share
increased from 9.21p to 9.26p.
</TEXT>
