<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / UK Company News: Airtours keen to embark on another hostile
bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PALMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AIRTOURS, the tour operator, is keen to embark on another hostile bid after
its failure to acquire its rival, Owners Abroad, earlier this year, Mr David
Crossland, Airtours chairman, said yesterday.
Speaking to the Association of British Travel Agents' convention in Majorca,
he said that when Owners Abroad published its next full-year results its
shareholders would be better able to judge whether or not Airtours had
offered a fair price.
Mr Crossland said he had learned from the Owners Abroad bid: 'The one thing
I did learn about the City is that there are some people there who are like
rhinoceroses. They are thick-skinned and they charge a lot.' He added,
however: 'I'd love to do it again.'
He said the bid for Owners Abroad had failed for three reasons. The first
was the success of Mr Howard Klein, Owners Abroad chairman, in persuading
LTU, the German company which owns Thomas Cook, to make a financial
commitment to ensuring that Airtours was defeated.
The second was that the Takeover Panel had applied the rules relating to
concert parties more vigorously to Airtours than to Owners Abroad.
The third was the defection of a previously-supportive institutional
investor to Owners Abroad. This is believed to have been a reference to
Gartmore, the investment manager.
Mr Crossland said that if Airtours looked outside the UK for future
acquisitions, Germany would be his favoured market.
</TEXT>
