<PROFILE>_AN-DD2CUAFGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / UK Company News: Improvement in property values seen by
Brixton
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRIXTON Estate, the seventh largest property company in the UK, produced a 4
per cent rise in pre-tax profits from Pounds 27.4m to Pounds 28.5m for 1992.
Its net asset value per share fell by 19 per cent, from 226p to 183p.
Mr Harry Axton, the chairman who will retire this summer, was encouraged by
the number of inquiries from potential tenants. 'I think that by the end of
the year we will start to see an improvement in values,' he said.
Value of the portfolio at the year-end dropped from Pounds 724m to Pounds
679m. The portfolio is split between the UK, which accounts for 83 per cent
of the total, and Belgium, Germany and Australia, representing the
remainder.
The UK portfolio, half of which is industrial property, is concentrated on
the western half of the home counties and, in London, at Holborn and in the
City.
Net rental income rose by 9 per cent to Pounds 55.2m (Pounds 50.7m).
Interest costs increased to Pounds 24.1m (Pounds 20.8m); another Pounds
11.6m of interest was capitalised.
The proportion of empty property in the portfolio increased marginally to
7.5 per cent, reflecting the rising number of UK tenants experiencing
financial difficulties. In the year the company leased 486,000 sq ft of
space, of which over 200,000 sq ft came from the development programme. A
further 140,000 sq ft was under offer.
A provision of Pounds 16.5m was made against the value of the development
properties this time.
The company has sites with planning permission for 600,000 sq ft of space.
'As soon as there is a clear trend in the right direction we shall restart
our development programme,' said Mr Axton.
Earnings per share increased from 12.64p to 13.86p. A final dividend of
5.35p makes 8.35p for the year (8.1p).
COMMENT
Brixton Estate is one of few property companies to survive the crash with
its reputation intact. Its prudent management and successful development
programme has given it a loyal following in the City, which in recent months
has placed the shares on a premium to net asset value. But yesterday's
results, with their larger-than-expected fall in property values,
disappointed investors, and the shares were marked down 8p to 177p. With
gearing of 114 per cent the company has little room to exploit opportunities
in the market, unless it sells property, raises new money or benefits from a
recovery in values. The potential for dividend growth is limited; if
capitalised interest is stripped out, the dividend would not currently be
covered. Assuming a net asset value of 170p for 1993, the shares are on a
narrow discount of 4 per cent. They are probably fully priced until the
company gets more fire-power or the recovery in the property market becomes
more convincing.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Brixton Estate.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6552 Subdividers and Developers, Ex Cemeteries.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>FIN  Annual report.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
