<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / UK Company News: C&amp;J Clark dissenters reveal plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of shareholders in C&amp;J Clark, opposed to the Pounds 184m bid from
Berisford International recommended by a majority of the private shoe
group's board, yesterday outlined its alternative to the takeover. The plan
was sent to shareholders in a letter.
The dissident group, which has adopted the acronym Shoes, said its plan was
for a shareholder council and a flotation of the company. This would lead to
'future stability', Mr Hugh Pym of Shoes said, advising shareholders to turn
down the offer.
Terms from Berisford, the property and trading group, comprise 213p in cash
or securities plus 26p of deferred cash from the planned sale of properties.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountants, this week completed the twice yearly
valuation of Clark shares putting a price on them of 100p.
The next few days will be crucial in the Clark saga as the various factions
put their cases to meetings with shareholders and employees, culminating in
an extraordinary meeting on May 7 when Berisford's proposals will be put to
a vote.
Mr Alan Mackay, finance director of Clark, said the Shoes letter was 'not
helpful at all and I do not think it (the plan) is deliverable.'
A previous attempt to float Clark failed when insufficient shareholders
voted in favour of necessary changes to the company's pre-emptive rights
structure.
Mr Mackay said the seven directors who recommended the bid 'feel the offer
from Berisford has the merit of certainty and solves a number of problems
which have been bedevilling Clarks for years.'
Setting up a shareholder council, representing family members, would lead to
a two-tier board. Mr Mackay said this 'does not appear to represent a simple
solution'.
Mr Alan Bowkett, chief executive of Berisford, said that a shareholder
council would tend to increase the conflict at Clark, not reduce it.
He said Shoes' commitment to a flotation was not something Shoes, none of
whose representatives are officers of the company, could deliver and it
revealed a lack of knowledge of the Stock Exchange rule book.
Shoes argued that the shares are worth 278p - the net asset value in the
latest balance sheet.
Mr Bowkett asked 'is Mr Pym making an offer of 278p? Is he promising 278p?
It is all rather misleading.'
</TEXT>
