<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Eagle Star man joins Bermuda reinsurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL BUTT, former chief executive of Eagle Star, the UK insurer, is to
become vice-chairman of Mid-Ocean, the recently formed Bermuda-based
catastrophe reinsurer. His appointment marks a strengthening of management
resources at Mid-Ocean, which has grown rapidly since its formation late
last year and comes amid signs of increasing investor interest in the
high-risk catastrophe reinsurance market.
Shrinkage of capacity and rapidly increasing rates have increased prospects
for profitability in a market which has recently suffered heavy losses.
Earlier this week it emerged that Mr John Head, the Manhattan-based
financier, was aiming to raise Dollars 100m (Pounds 64m) to form a London
reinsurance company.
The brighter outlook for the reinsurance market will be an important selling
point for Lloyd's of London, which will announce today how it intends to
attract corporate investors to the market.
Mr Butt is the only insurance executive to have lost his job as a result of
the industry's exposure to mortgage indemnity insurances. He spent just over
a year with Phoenix Securities, the corporate finance boutique, advising on
mergers and acquisitions in the insurance industry. At Mid-Ocean he will
play a prominent executive role, alongside Mr Ian Heap, the group's
president. Based in Bermuda, he will have responsibility for administration
and worldwide marketing.
Launched with capital of Dollars 400m last October by Marsh McLennan, the
New York-based insurance broker, and JP Morgan, the merchant bank, Mid-Ocean
has already earned more than Dollars 50m in premium income and could exceed
the Dollars 200m target set for its first year.
Mr Butt says he believes the growth of the Bermudan market will help rather
than hinder recovery in the London market. 'The window of opportunity for
Mid-Ocean was widening as a result of continued withdrawals from the market
in recent months,' he said.
The company is one of a number of new insurance ventures formed in Bermuda
in the past few months. Earlier this year, Marsh and Morgan were also
involved in the launch of a Dollars 70m Bermuda-based venture, Underwriting
Capital (Merrett).
</TEXT>
